<Document>
<name>Mallorca Tramuntana — MA-10 with Sa Calobra spur</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Mallorca Tramuntana — MA-10 with Sa Calobra spur</h2><p><i>Mallorca, Spain · MA-10, Pollença to Andratx, with MA-2141 to Sa Calobra</i></p><p><b>UNESCO mountain spine of Mallorca with the world-famous 'Tie Knot' switchback at Sa Calobra.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>76 km (47 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>4–5 hrs</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>April–May and October (avoid August)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Cyclists in spring (thousands), tour buses, narrow shoulders, blind hairpins on Sa Calobra</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>189</td></tr></table><hr><p>Mallorca's mountain spine, the Serra de Tramuntana, was named UNESCO World Heritage in 2011 — recognition of 1,000 years of human terracing on a near-vertical landscape. The MA-10 follows the spine; the MA-2141 spur down to Sa Calobra is the famous one — 14 km of switchbacks ending at a hidden cove, including the 'Nus de sa Corbata' (Tie Knot), a road that loops over itself in a single 270° hairpin. The Tramuntana is Lance Armstrong's preferred winter training ground; spandex outnumbers cars in spring. Drive the loop from Pollença west to Andratx, with the Sa Calobra detour from the MA-10 high point. October light is the season's secret — soft gold on olive groves and pale limestone.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Lluc Monastery</b> — 13th-century Marian pilgrimage site; the Black Madonna of Lluc is Mallorca's patron. The boys' choir (Es Blauets, 'the Little Blues') sings most mornings.</li><li><b>Nus de sa Corbata</b> — The 'Tie Knot' — a single 270° hairpin where the road crosses over itself on a stone arch. Park at the upper hairpin to walk down and look up at the geometry.</li><li><b>Sa Calobra cove</b> — Hidden pebble beach at the mouth of the Torrent de Pareis canyon. Walk through the tunnel from the road end to the beach.</li><li><b>Sóller &amp; vintage tram to Port de Sóller</b> — Orange-grove valley town. The 1913 wooden tram (Tranvia de Sóller) descends to the port — works daily, costs €8.</li><li><b>Deià</b> — Tiny terraced mountain village. Robert Graves moved here in 1929 and is buried in the church cemetery; his house is now a museum.</li><li><b>Valldemossa Charterhouse</b> — Carthusian monastery where Chopin and George Sand wintered 1838–39. Sand's account, A Winter in Majorca, is what made Mallorca's mountains famous to outsiders.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
